subSection.paragraph:
Type
2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) is a chronic disease defined by insulin resistance and high levels of sugar in the blood (
Olokoba et al., 2012
). T2DM consists of around 90% of diabetes cases (
Moneva and Dagogo-Jack, 2002
). The World Health Organization (WHO) Global report on diabetes reveals that the number of adults suffering from diabetes had nearly fourfold since 1980 to 422 million adults, and it is predicted to reach 693 million by 2045 (
Artasensi et al., 2020
). To treat T2DM, a variety of different 
types
of diabetes drugs has been used such as acarbose, miglitol and voglibose. However, these drugs cause some side effects namely diarrhoea, gas and upset stomach (
Ismail and Deshmukh, 2012
; 
Oboh et al., 2016
). Thus, the search for new potent α- glucosidase inhibitors from plants is necessary.

The unusual structures of compounds 1–6 motivated us to study their plausible biosynthesis pathway (
Fig. 5
). First, thymol (I) was obtained from geranyl diphosphate (
Krause et al., 2021
), and this precursor is transformed into Ia through ethylation and oxidation processes. Intermediate II could be formed by the Claisen–Schmidt condensation reaction between ketone Ia and gallic aldehyde. Then, dimethylallyl pyrophosphate could become an electrophile to attack the double bond of II, followed by loss of proton and then cyclisation to create intermediate IIIa. After that, 1 could be constructed from aromatisation, hydration, oxidation and methylation. Finally, the nucleophilic intramolecular addition of 1 afforded 2 and 3, which underwent methylation or ethylation to produce 4–6.

The chromatographic materials and instruments were the same as those previously published (
Le et al., 2022
).

The α- glucosidase inhibition assay was performed according to previous protocols (
Ramadhan and Phuwapraisirisan, 2015
), and the DPPH assay followed the method described in the literature (Rankovic´et al., 2012). Experiments were performed in triplicate. The results were described as the mean ± SD of three independent experiments.
